    thinking: "**Defining the Database Structure**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on defining the precise schema for the Postgres database on Supabase. I\'m focusing on the best way to structure the tables for purchase receipts, including fields like amount, vendor, date, and category. I am considering the implications for generating monthly spending reports and aim for a structure that facilitates clear data retrieval and analysis.\n\n\n**Refining the App Features**\n\nI\'m now iterating on the core features. The plan is to implement form-based receipt entry and an AI-powered parsing feature using Gemini 3.5 Flash for extracting data from raw receipt text. My focus is now on Supabase integration and credential management. I\'m prioritizing user-friendly setup, considering `.env` storage for security, and exploring options for handling Supabase connection credentials, such as environment variables.\n\n\n**Evaluating Database Connectors**\n\nI\'m now comparing `@supabase/supabase-js` versus the standard `pg` driver for connecting to the Postgres database. While the Supabase package offers simplicity, the `pg` driver provides a more raw Postgres connection, which allows a clean configuration panel for users to set their Supabase URL and keys, or use a default database. I\'m aiming for flexibility and user-friendliness, supporting both connection methods or providing a fallback. Moreover, I\'m considering a full-stack Express server to handle CRUD operations on receipts and an elegant dashboard with reports, charts, and vendor analysis.\n\n\n"
